prompts.prompt:
Act as a Staff AI Engineer at an Indian SaaS company. I need a decision tree to pick between Claude 3.5 Sonnet, GPT-4o, Llama-3-70B (self-hosted on Modal/vLLM), and Gemini 1.5 Pro for a new feature.

Feature context: {{describe feature: e.g., contract clause extraction, customer support reply, code review, summarisation}}
Expected QPS: {{number}}
Monthly token volume (input + output): {{millions}}
Latency SLO: {{p95 ms}}
Data residency: {{India-only / global / hybrid}}
Budget ceiling: INR {{amount}}/month

Produce:
1. A decision tree (Mermaid) with 4-6 leaf nodes mapping to a specific model + hosting choice (API vs self-host on Modal/Together/Sarvam).
2. Cost-per-1000-token table in INR (use current rates: Claude Sonnet ~INR 0.25 input / 1.25 output, GPT-4o ~INR 0.21 / 0.83, Gemini ~INR 0.10 / 0.42, Llama-3-70B on Together ~INR 0.07 blended). Show monthly bill for each model at my volume.
3. Latency profile (p50 / p95) from public benchmarks; flag which models meet my SLO.
4. Data residency verdict: which providers offer India region (Azure OpenAI India, Bedrock Mumbai, Vertex Mumbai) vs which require self-host for DPDP-Act compliance.
5. Quality benchmark: pick 2 evals relevant to my feature (MMLU, HumanEval, IFEval, MT-Bench, Indic-bench) and show scores.
6. Final recommendation with 3 reasons and 1 explicit risk.
7. Migration plan: how to A/B test the chosen model against a fallback in production using LiteLLM proxy or a custom router.

Be opinionated. If I am asking for GPT-4o on a low-margin feature that ships 50M tokens/month, tell me to use Llama-3-70B on Together AI and explain the INR savings.

You are a Principal AI Engineer. Write a 1-page decision memo for my CTO answering: should we RAG, fine-tune, or do both for the following use case?

Use case: {{e.g., legal-research bot over Indian Supreme Court judgments, internal HR policy assistant, customer-support reply over Razorpay docs}}
Corpus size: {{number of documents and total tokens}}
Update frequency: {{daily / weekly / static}}
Query complexity: {{factual lookup / multi-hop reasoning / stylistic generation}}
Expected accuracy bar: {{%}}
Latency SLO: {{ms}}
Team size: {{ML engineers}}
GPU access: {{none / A100 on Modal / on-prem}}

Structure the memo:
1. TL;DR recommendation in 2 lines (RAG / LoRA fine-tune / full fine-tune / hybrid).
2. Decision matrix with 6 axes: corpus volatility, query type, accuracy, latency, cost, team capability — score each option 1-5 and total.
3. Cost model: RAG (embedding cost + vector DB INR/month + retrieval LLM tokens) vs LoRA (one-time training INR + serving infra + base API tokens) vs full fine-tune. Use INR and assume Indian cloud pricing.
4. Risks: hallucination control, data drift, knowledge cut-off, eval coverage, DPDP-Act exposure if PII enters training data.
5. Build sequence: phase 0 baseline prompt, phase 1 vanilla RAG, phase 2 hybrid retrieval + re-ranker, phase 3 fine-tune ONLY IF eval gap remains.
6. Eval plan: 100-question golden set, retrieval recall@5, faithfulness, answer-correctness, latency, cost-per-query.
7. When to revisit decision (e.g., quarterly or when corpus crosses X tokens).

Rule: never recommend fine-tuning before exhausting prompt + RAG iterations unless the use case is a stylistic / format-locked transformation. Justify if you violate this.

Act as an AI Eval Lead. I am building evals for an LLM feature and do not know which metrics to use. Help me pick the right metric stack.

Feature: {{describe: classification, extraction, summarisation, QA, code-gen, agent-task, RAG-answer, translation Indic <-> English}}
Ground truth availability: {{labelled set size / none / synthetic only}}
Failure cost: {{low / medium / high — e.g., wrong loan-eligibility answer is high}}
Volume of inferences/day: {{number}}

Produce:
1. Metric tree: for my task type, list 3-6 candidate metrics across categories (deterministic: BLEU/ROUGE/exact-match/F1; semantic: BERTScore, embedding-cosine; LLM-judge: faithfulness, relevance, helpfulness, harmfulness; behavioural: latency, cost-INR, refusal rate, format adherence).
2. For each metric: when to use, when it lies, INR cost to compute (LLM-judge calls add up), and tooling (Ragas, DeepEval, promptfoo, OpenAI Evals, Langfuse).
3. Pick 3 PRIMARY metrics + 2 GUARDRAIL metrics for my feature; justify in 2 lines each.
4. Eval set design: how many examples (rule of thumb: 100 to start, 500 for shipping, 2000 for fine-tuning), stratification (by user persona, by language Hindi/Tamil/Bengali/English, by difficulty), and how to source (production logs with consent, synthetic, hand-written).
5. LLM-as-judge prompt template with reasoning-first output and a calibration step using 50 human-labelled examples to measure judge agreement (Cohen kappa target > 0.6).
6. Regression workflow: CI gate that fails if primary metric drops > 3% on the golden set.
7. Pitfall list: 5 common mistakes Indian teams make (e.g., evaluating only English when 30% of users type in Hinglish).

Act as a fine-tuning specialist. I am considering fine-tuning {{base model: Llama-3-8B / Mistral-7B / Qwen-2-7B / Llama-3-70B}} for {{task}}. Should I do LoRA, QLoRA, full fine-tune, or DPO?

Dataset size: {{number of examples}}
Dataset quality: {{describe}}
GPU budget: {{e.g., 4xA100 80GB on Modal at INR X/hr or 8xH100 on-prem}}
Serving infra: {{vLLM on Modal / Together / TGI / on-prem}}
Latency SLO: {{ms}}
Update cadence: {{one-time / monthly retrain}}

Deliver:
1. Decision: LoRA / QLoRA / full FT / DPO / SFT+DPO. One-line reason.
2. Decision matrix scoring 5 axes: data size needed, GPU INR cost, quality ceiling, serving complexity (multi-LoRA vs single weight), ease of iteration.
3. Hyperparameter starter pack: rank, alpha, learning rate, epochs, batch, gradient accumulation, packing. Justify each.
4. Dataset prep SOP: dedup, decontamination against eval set, length filtering, format (ChatML vs Llama3 template), train/val/test split (80/10/10 stratified).
5. Training cost estimate in INR: GPU-hours x rate; expect LoRA on 10k examples for 8B model = ~2 A100-hours = INR ~600.
6. Serving plan: vLLM with multi-LoRA adapters (cheap multi-tenant) vs merged weights (faster, single tenant). INR per 1M tokens served.
7. Eval strategy: held-out test set + production-like prompts + LLM-judge; required quality lift over base + RAG to justify FT (suggest > 8% on primary metric).
8. Failure modes: catastrophic forgetting, format collapse, refusal regression. Mitigations.
9. DPDP note: ensure training data has consent and PII is masked.
10. Rollback plan if quality regresses post-deploy.
